## Petrol Crisis in country due to war 

Recently, I have been witnessing something that hits close to home — the ongoing petrol crisis in our country.
Due to the wars and conflicts between different nations across the world, fuel supply chains have been severely disrupted, causing petrol prices to skyrocket and shortages to spread.
I see it every day — long queues at petrol stations, people waiting for hours just to fill their tanks, and the rising cost affecting everything from transport to daily groceries.
It is a stark reminder of how deeply connected we are to global events, and how a conflict thousands of miles away can shake the lives of ordinary people like us right here at home.

## Online Classes During Petrol Crises

On top of everything, attending online classes during this crisis has been an incredibly frustrating experience.
The petrol shortage has worsened load shedding across the country, which means my internet cuts off right in the middle of lectures and assignments are harder to submit on time.
Data packages are expensive and not everyone can afford to stay connected for hours every day.
There are moments when I am sitting in the dark with my phone on low battery, trying to catch whatever I can from a buffering class recording.
It is not just a technical inconvenience — it is emotionally draining to feel like you are falling behind despite giving your best effort under such difficult circumstances.
